I am designing a class named `InventoryItem`. It represents a item in a game inventory. You could have multiples of the same item. Because of that, the class implements the getter and setter of the integer `Count`, that represents the number of items in the inventory.

`Count` has two constraints.

 - It must be greater or equal than `zero`.
 - It must be lower than `MAX_ITEM_COUNT` (e.g. 30), a constant.

Now suppose the caller of `Count` assigns an integer out of the bounds defined in the constraints.

```c#
InventoryItem myInventoryItem;
// ...
myInventoryItem.Count = 35;
```

**QUESTION: Is it a best practice to throw a `System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException` or to clamp the argument value to the range defined by the constraints?**

-----

Here it is a sample implementation of the InventoryItem class:

```c#
public class InventoryItem
{
    private const int MAX_ITEM_COUNT = 30;
        
    private InventoryItem _inventoryItem;
    private int _count;

    // 
    // ... other class methods and constructors
    //

    public int Count
    {
        set
        {
            // Should i throw this exception?
            if( value &lt; 0 )
                 throw new System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException();
        
            // Or fix argument by enforcing invariant?
            this._count = Math.Min(MAX_ITEM_COUNT, Math.Max(0, value));
        }
        get =&gt; this._count;
    }
}
```
-----------

**Both sides of the argument:**

After researching, I landed on two opposing arguments:

- You should throw `System.ArgumentOutOfRangeException` because the value should respect the bounds contraint and it is a fundamental assumption of the current code block.

- You should clamp the value because you should only throw an exception when there&#39;s nothing you can do to get out of your current state. And in this case, it is possible to get out of the current state and guarantee the constraints by clamping the value to the desired range.

----

**Other references:**

There is some similar debate on https://stackoverflow.com/questions/77127/when-to-throw-an-exception, but I was not able to come with a definitive answer to my question by the discussion there.

The c# documentation [Best practices for exceptions](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/standard/exceptions/best-practices-for-exceptions) states that one should &quot;Handle common conditions without throwing exceptions&quot;.

However, I then asked myself. If I tried to call the `Count` method passing the value `35` (an invalid value) and it handled my request by setting it `30`, wouldn&#39;t that be a behavior different from the one I requested? Should the class really change my invalid request to a valid one?

